... About Diabetes What is diabetes? Signs and symptoms
If you have diabetes you may experience a range of signs and symptoms. These
will present differently depending on whether you have type 1 or type 2
Type 1 diabetes is an autoimmune condition that is often diagnosed in
childhood, although you can develop it at any age.
The signs and symptoms of type 1 diabetes can develop suddenly over a few days
or weeks. They can be severe and, if left untreated, life-threatening. Being
Signs and symptoms of type 1 diabetes may include:
* Excessive thirst and drinking a lot of fluids
**If you or a member of your family are experiencing one or more of these
symptoms you should make an urgent appointment to see your doctor.**
Type 2 diabetes is a progressive condition that tends to develop gradually. As
a result, the signs and symptoms may develop very slowly. You may not notice
the signs or symptoms at all, or you may dismiss them as a normal part of
This can mean that by the time you notice something, you may have been living
with diabetes for some years, and you could be at risk of developing
complications. In some cases, those complications may be the first sign that
* Passing urine more frequently, commonly noticed at night
* Having cuts, sores or ulcers that heal slowly
* Weight changes – commonly a gradual increase in weight
* Pain or tingling in the lower legs and/or feet
**If you notice one or more of these signs or symptoms, you should make an
Early detection and treatment of diabetes can prevent the development of
serious, and in some cases life-threatening, health problems.
